[src:cleveland-spiders-all-time-roster/1887-cleveland-blues-season] The **1887 Cleveland Blues** baseball team finished with a 39–92 record, last in the American Association during their debut season.
[src:cleveland-spiders-all-time-roster/1887-cleveland-blues-season] Organized by streetcar tycoon Frank Robison, the team played its home games at National League Park.
[src:cleveland-spiders-all-time-roster/1887-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1887 throughout the world.
[src:cleveland-spiders-all-time-roster/1888-cleveland-blues-season] The **1888 Cleveland Blues** baseball team finished with a 50–82 record, sixth place in the American Association.
[src:cleveland-spiders-all-time-roster/1889-cleveland-spiders-season] Before the 1889 season, the Cleveland Blues switched from the American Association to the National League.
[src:cleveland-spiders-all-time-roster/1889-cleveland-spiders-season] They also earned a new nickname, the **Cleveland Spiders**, because so many of their players were very thin.
[src:cleveland-spiders-all-time-roster/1889-cleveland-spiders-season] They finished their first season in the National League with a 61–72 record, good enough for sixth place.
[src:cleveland-spiders-all-time-roster/1890-cleveland-spiders-season] The **1890 Cleveland Spiders** finished with a 44–88 record and a seventh-place finish in the National League.
[src:cleveland-spiders-all-time-roster/1890-cleveland-spiders-season] The team played six straight home games in Indianapolis, Indiana at Indianapolis Park between July 28 and August 2 against the Brooklyn Bridegrooms and New York Giants.
[src:cleveland-spiders-all-time-roster/1890-cleveland-spiders-season] It was a former Sunday-games ballpark of the Indianapolis Hoosiers who had folded at the end of the previous season.
[src:cleveland-spiders-all-time-roster/1891-cleveland-spiders-season] The **1891 Cleveland Spiders season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:cleveland-spiders-all-time-roster/1891-cleveland-spiders-season] They finished with a 65–74 record and a fifth-place finish in the National League.
[src:cleveland-spiders-all-time-roster/1891-cleveland-spiders-season] The Spiders moved to a new ballpark in 1891.
[src:cleveland-spiders-all-time-roster/1891-cleveland-spiders-season] League Park was financed by Spiders owner Frank Robison, and it would be the team's home for the remainder of their existence.
[src:cleveland-spiders-all-time-roster/1891-cleveland-spiders-season] It would also be home to the Cleveland Indians.
[src:cleveland-spiders-all-time-roster/1891-cleveland-spiders-season] Patsy Tebeau, the team's starting third baseman, was named manager midway through the season.
[src:cleveland-spiders-all-time-roster/1891-cleveland-spiders-season] He remained the Spiders manager until his contract was reassigned to the St.
[src:cleveland-spiders-all-time-roster/1892-cleveland-spiders-season] The **1892 Cleveland Spiders**, led by star pitcher Cy Young, finished with a 93–56 overall record, second-best in the National League.
[src:cleveland-spiders-all-time-roster/1892-cleveland-spiders-season] In the first split season in Major League Baseball history, the Spiders finished in fifth place during the first half of the season, and in first place during the second half.
[src:cleveland-spiders-all-time-roster/1892-cleveland-spiders-season] After the season, they played against the first-half champions, the Boston Beaneaters, in the "World's Championship Series", which the Spiders lost, five games to none (with one tie).
[src:cleveland-spiders-all-time-roster/cleveland-spiders-all-time-roster] The following is a list of players and who appeared in at least one game for the Cleveland Spiders franchise of Major League Baseball from 1887 through 1899.
[src:cleveland-spiders-all-time-roster/cleveland-spiders-all-time-roster] This includes both the Cleveland Blues of the American Association and the Cleveland Spiders of the National League.
[src:cleveland-spiders-all-time-roster/cleveland-spiders-all-time-roster] Players in **bold** are in the Baseball Hall of Fame.
